content:
To design a segment of code that loops from 0 to 10 and displays the square values of each iteration, you can use a simple loop construct in your preferred programming language. Below are examples in a few popular languages:

### Python
```python
for i in range(11):
    print(f"The square of {i} is {i**2}")
```

### JavaScript
```javascript
for (let i = 0; i <= 10; i++) {
    console.log(`The square of ${i} is ${i * i}`);
}
```

### Java
```java
public class SquareValues {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        for (int i = 0; i <= 10; i++) {
            System.out.println("The square of " + i + " is " + (i * i));
        }
    }
}
```

### C++
```cpp
#include <iostream>

int main() {
    for (int i = 0; i <= 10; i++) {
        std::cout << "The square of " << i << " is " << (i * i) << std::endl;
    }
    return 0;
}
```

### C#
```csharp
using System;

class Program {
    static void Main() {
        for (int i = 0; i <= 10; i++) {
            Console.WriteLine($"The square of {i} is {i * i}");
        }
    }
}
```

You can choose any of these code snippets based on your preferred programming language. Each one will loop from 0 to 10 and print the square of each number in that range.
